==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rapt
<hw>Rapt</hw> <pr>(r⟦acr⟧pt)</pr>, <def><pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> of
<er>Rap</er>, to snatch away.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rapt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Rapt
<hw>Rapt</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Snatched away; hurried
away or along.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Waters <qex>rapt</qex> with whirling away.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Transported with love, admiration, delight, etc.;
enraptured.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>rapt</xex> musician.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Longfellow.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Wholly absorbed or engrossed, as in work or
meditation.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Rapt</xex> in secret studies.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rapt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Rapt
<hw>Rapt</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From F. <ets>rapt</ets> abduction,
rape, L. <ets>raptus</ets>, fr. <ets>rapere</ets> to seize and carry
off, to transport; or fr. E. <ets>rapt</ets>, a. See <er>Rapt</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>, and <er>Rapid</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An ecstasy; a
trance.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Bp. Morton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Rapidity.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir T.
Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rapt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Rapt
<hw>Rapt</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To transport or
ravish.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Drayton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To carry away by force.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Daniel.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rapter</ent>⟦br⟧
